result.execSummary:
The defendant Harley R. Est was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Issue of Worthless Checks(<=$2500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.24(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Fredrickson.  Defendant plead guilty to Count 1.  Counts 2 through 6 dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.  Court advised the defendant of the charge and possible penalties she plead to.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, elements and constitutional rights with the defendant.  Defense stipulated to a factual basis for the plea.  Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her constitutional rights and entered her plea.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Count 1.  Joint recommendation on count 1 is 2 years probation with conditions.  Defendant did not elect to exercise her right to allocution.  Court ordered:  Sentence withheld, 2 years probation.  Restitution, plus restitution surcharges. Pay monthly, through probation.  Seek and maintain employment.    The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.  Not to issue any checks, unless agent approves.  May apply for expugment if she successfully completes her probation and diversion agreement.  Subject to random testing.  CC.
